         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1959"/><citedRange>252</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>314</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1959"/><citedRange>252</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the more evil ... [fem.pl.]. </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:knoll1996"/><citedRange>95</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1959"/><citedRange>252</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>404</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1959"/><citedRange>252</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>201</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... two thousand worms devour him, two thousand [devour his] forehead, two thousand right there in the eyes ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1966"/><citedRange>268</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1967c"/><citedRange>180</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1972"/><citedRange>430</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Worms devour his head and face day and night ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... having to evoke pity in the lovely face the worm(s) ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:couvreur1959"/><citedRange>252</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:burlakanditkin2010"/><citedRange>355</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2014"/><citedRange>92-93</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [There is] a fight between vultures [and] jackals [that] belong to the cemetery. ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">For the meaning of <w lemmaRef="A_lepś"/> and <w lemmaRef="A_sukrāṃ"/>, see <bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2014"/><citedRange>92-93</citedRange></bibl> after a proposal by <bibl><title corresp="ref:burlakanditkin2010"/><citedRange>355</citedRange></bibl>; note in addition that jackals and vultures are depicted on cemetery scenes from Qizil Caves 116 and 220; see <bibl><title corresp="ref:howardandvignato2014"/><citedRange>109</citedRange></bibl>. While we follow the semantic proposal by <bibl><title corresp="ref:burlakanditkin2010"/></bibl>, their syntactic interpretation of the sentence is hardly possible.</note></p>
         </div>
